.SS Terrain and replay
.sp
\fB\&.bin\fP data files are either a terrain heightfield (a 513×513 grid of signed 16\-bit samples) or a
tile\-flag map (a 128×128 grid of unsigned 16\-bit values); the shape is detected from the file size
and decoded to JSON. \fB\&.ctl\fP files are demo/replay input recordings of 16\-byte records, decoded to
a JSON list.
.SS Save and snapshot state
.sp
The save, config, level, and debug\-snapshot files (\fB\&.sav\fP, \fB\&.cfg\fP, \fB\&.lev\fP, and \fB\&.xxx\fP) are
\fBmemcpy\fP\-style images of game RAM. Their schemas were reverse\-engineered from the PC executable
(\fBincoming.exe\fP), so the decoders map the real in\-memory layout rather than treating the body as
opaque. Every byte is decoded into a typed value, so the output is both human\-inspectable and
lossless; nothing is left as a base64 blob.
.sp
The configuration file (\fB\&.cfg\fP, written by \fBSaveGameConfigFile\fP) is a concatenation of
fixed\-size blocks described by the game\(aqs internal save\-descriptor table, totalling 10980 bytes.
It is split into its 21 named blocks, each decoded into a readable value:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
the build stamp and the trailing text buffers as strings;
.IP \(bu 2
the keybind block as four control\-config pages of ten slots, each
\fB{directInputScancode, name}\fP where the name is the W3C \fBKeyboardEvent.code\fP for the bound
DirectInput scancode (special input codes become \fBspecial<n>\fP; an unbound slot has an empty
name);
.IP \(bu 2
the options block as the serial/modem multiplayer connection settings: COM port, baud rate, stop
bits, parity, and flow control;
.IP \(bu 2
the high\-score block as a list of tables, each with its category id, sub\-index, and nine
\fB{score, name}\fP entries;
.IP \(bu 2
the input\-options, camera\-state, joystick\-binding, and input\-state blocks as objects of named
fields (the same field\-table approach used for the snapshots);
.IP \(bu 2
the saved\-mission\-slot table as a list of ten \fB{name, missionSlot, levelValue}\fP slots;
.IP \(bu 2
the force\-feedback flag as a boolean;
.IP \(bu 2
the checksum as \fB{stored, computed, valid}\fP, where \fBcomputed\fP is a signed\-byte sum recomputed
over the high\-score block and \fBvalid\fP reports whether the two agree.
.UNINDENT
.sp
The snapshot files share one field table derived from the contiguous run of game globals that the
engine serialises. \fB\&.sav\fP and \fB\&.xxx\fP (\fBSaveMissionStateSnapshot\fP) cover the whole region;
\fB\&.lev\fP (\fBSaveLevelStateSnapshot\fP) is the same region without its 12\-byte leading mission\-id
prefix, so it reuses the same table shifted by that prefix. Each decoded field carries its game
variable name (mission and game\-mode flags, camera and replay\-camera state, the script runtime,
score statistics, frame and timer counters, lighting and fog state, the saved CD\-audio track, and
more). Run\-time pointer fields are decoded as unsigned 32\-bit words; their saved values are not
meaningful across sessions.
.sp
The largest part of a snapshot is the world\-object pool, an array of 1700 204\-byte \fBGameObject\fP
records; it is decoded as \fBworldObjectPool\fP, a list of objects with named fields (position,
orientation vectors, type and class ids, behaviour and effect state, lifetime, and so on). The
128×128 world spatial grid (\fBworldGrid\fP) and the script process and label tables
(\fBscriptProcTable\fP, \fBscriptLabelTable\fP) are likewise decoded. A few smaller pools that are not
yet fully reverse\-engineered remain as \fBunknownAt_<offset>\fP arrays.
.sp
Across every decoded block and snapshot, field names are emitted as plain camelCase (the game\(aqs
Hungarian prefixes are stripped); each \fB*Flags\fP bitfield is expanded into an object of one boolean
per bit, using the reverse\-engineered name for bits whose meaning is known (for example
\fBnetGameFlags\fP exposes \fBdeathmatch\fP, \fBteamMode\fP, and \fBtimedMission\fP) and \fBbit<n>\fP for the
rest; and split \fB*Lo\fP/\fB*Hi\fP dword pairs are combined into a single 64\-bit field.
.SS Dreamcast \fB\&.TXT\fP text
.sp
Dreamcast \fB\&.TXT\fP files are re\-encoded to UTF\-8. The source encoding is detected in order: UTF\-8,
then Shift\-JIS (Japanese), then ISO\-8859\-15 (French, German, Spanish, and Italian). Pure\-ASCII files
are already valid UTF\-8 and pass through unchanged.
.SH API REFERENCE
.sp
Module\-level reference for the public \fBincoming_extractor\fP package. The command\-line entry points
are documented separately under \fI\%Usage\fP and \fI\%Utilities\fP\&.
.SS Core
.sp
The top\-level modules that drive a run: source detection, the mirroring dispatcher, the ambient
per\-run context, the texture and pack readers, and native\-tool location.
.SS \fBincoming_extractor.context\fP
.sp
Ambient per\-conversion context.
.sp
Converters that resolve sibling assets (for example a model\(aqs textures) need to know the root of the
source tree, and they may need an explicit path to a native helper tool. Rather than thread these
through every converter signature, the dispatcher and the command line publish them here for the
duration of a run.
